The area of $CMJKN$ is equal to the sum of the areas of $\triangle AMC$ and $\triangle BNC$ minus the sum of the areas of $\triangle AMJ$ and $\triangle BNK$.  Since all of these triangles have height $x$, we can use the bases shown to compute:

\begin{align*}
\text{Area}\,(CMJKN)&=(4+x)(x)+(9+x)(x)-(4\cdot x+5\cdot x/2)\\
&=x^2+4x+9x+x^2-9x-x\\
&=2x^2+3x\\
&=3x(2+x).
\end{align*}Since $x$ is the height of the triangle, we know that $x$ must be positive.  Also, since the lengths of the sides of $\triangle ABC$ are $5$, $12$, and $13$, we see that $x$ cannot be greater than $5$, or else $\triangle AMC$ would not be a right triangle.  Thus, $x$ must be less than $5$ and greater than $0$, so $2+x$ must be greater than $2$.  Therefore, the area of $CMJKN$ is greater than $3\cdot 2=6$ but less than $3\cdot 5=15$.  The only answer choice in this range is $\boxed{\text{(D)}\ 240/13}$.

