Since $\triangle ABC$ is isosceles, $AB = AC.$  Let $h$ be the height of $\triangle ABC$ from vertex $A.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.15 cm);

pair A, B, C;

A = (10/sqrt(3),20);
B = (0,0);
C = (20,0);
draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw((0,0)--(20,0));
draw((0,0)--(10/sqrt(3),20));
label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$x$", (20,0), E);
label("$y$", (0,20), N);
label("$h$", (A + B)/2, W);
[/asy]

Then \[\frac{1}{2} \cdot h \cdot (AB + AC) = 240,\]so $\frac{1}{2} \cdot h \cdot (AB + AB) = 240,$ or $h \cdot AB = 120.$  Since $AB = AC,$ $AC = 120/h.$  Then \[BC = AB + AC = \frac{120}{h} + \frac{120}{h} = \frac{240}{h} = 20.\]Hence, $h = \frac{240}{20} = \boxed{12}.$
